ngland":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tilly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a shortened form of <b>Tilling</b>, which itself is a patronymic from   Till  .","English and Irish: variant of   Tilley  .","Irish: variant of   Tully  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Till","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Till</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Matild(e)</i> (in its Latin form <i>Matilda</i>), which was an alternative to <i>Maud</i>; see   Maude   2. A diminutive form occurs in   Tillotson  .","North German: variant of   Thiel  ."]}]},{"name":"Otes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a patronymic derived from the genitive case of the medieval given name <i>Ote</i> or <i>Ode</i> (of Norman, and ultimately Germanic, origin;  compare  Odette  ). In northern England the medieval given name survived into the 19th century. It came to be used as a given name in America in honour of the Revolutionary hero  James Otis  (  1725–